What is IAM?

AWS IAM (Identity and Access Management) – Short Summary

Users: Individual accounts with login or permanent credentials (access key + secret key)
Groups: Collections of users with shared permissions
Roles: Temporary access credentials via AWS STS ✅ for services or users
Policies: JSON rules that define what actions and Resource are allowed or denied

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:*",
        "dynamodb:*"
      ],
      "Resource": "*"
    }
  ]
}

👉 In short: IAM controls who can access what in AWS.
-------------------------------------

Roles: Temporary access identities for services or users

once service used the role does it delete automatically?

No, the role does NOT delete automatically.
---
How it actually works:

Lambda assumes IAM Role
        ↓
AWS STS (Security Token Service)
generates TEMPORARY credentials:
  Access Key ID     → expires in 1 hour
  Secret Access Key → expires in 1 hour
  Session Token     → expires in 1 hour
        ↓
Lambda uses credentials to call AWS APIs
        ↓
Credentials expire ✅ (auto deleted)
        ↓
Role still exists ❌ (never deleted)
        ↓
Next time Lambda runs →
  gets fresh temporary credentials again
-------
Role lifecycle:

Created:
  You create role once
  attach policies once
  assign to Lambda once
        ↓
Every Lambda invocation:
  Lambda assumes role
  gets temp credentials (1hr)
  does its work
  credentials expire ✅
  role stays ❌
        ↓
Role deleted:
  ONLY when you manually delete it
  or terraform destroy runs
  never automatic
---
Simple summary:

IAM Role:
  ❌ never deleted automatically
  ✅ stays forever until you delete

Temporary credentials:
  ✅ auto expire (15 min to 12 hours)
  ✅ new ones issued on next use
  ✅ this is what "temporary" means

"Temporary" in IAM Role =
  temporary CREDENTIALS
  NOT temporary role ✅

The role is permanent — only the credentials it generates are temporary!





